# Tailwind CSS v4 Guidelines

## Styling Approach

- Use Tailwind CSS v4 utility classes for styling
- Prefer utility classes over custom CSS when possible
- Keep custom CSS in `static/styles.css` only when absolutely necessary
- Use Tailwind's component classes and `@apply` directive sparingly

## Responsive Design

- Use Tailwind's responsive prefixes: `sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`, `xl:`, `2xl:`
- Follow mobile-first approach
- Test responsive layouts at different breakpoints

## Dark Mode

- Use Tailwind's dark mode classes when needed: `dark:`
- Ensure proper contrast in both light and dark modes
- Test dark mode appearance

## Best Practices

- Use semantic class names when grouping utilities
- Avoid inline styles - use Tailwind classes instead
- Keep utility class combinations readable
- Use Tailwind's spacing scale consistently
- Leverage Tailwind's color palette

## Custom Styles

- Only add custom CSS when Tailwind utilities are insufficient
- Place custom styles in `static/styles.css`
- Document why custom CSS is needed
- Consider creating reusable component classes if pattern repeats
